<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08093i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08093i">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08093i"> 93(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> which art in heaven / his = its</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The distinction between animate and inanimate now is much more accentuated than it used to be, and this has led to some other changes, of which the two most important are the creation (about 1600) of the form <i>its</i> (before that time <i>his</i> was neuter as well as masculine) and the restriction of the relative pronoun <i>which</i> to things: its old use alike for persons and things is seen in &lsquo;Our father <i>which</i> art in Heaven&rsquo;. <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJGS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#OJGS"><cite title="source">The Growth and Structure of the English Language</cite></a>, 4th ed. (Jul 1923) 186-7 [Gender]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
